  "case_id": "D2N200",
  "method": "medsum_ent",
  "template": "sectioned",
  "summary_text": "Chief Complaint\nHeadache and elevated blood pressure.\n\nHistory of Present Illness\nThe patient reports a long-standing history of high blood pressure, for which she was previously prescribed chlorthalidone, but she discontinued it due to stomach upset. She also experiences headaches, which are intermittent and throbbing, and she finds relief with Tylenol. She occasionally experiences dizziness and blurry vision. She admits to eating a lot of McDonald's, including their large fries, and reports forgetting to take her metformin medication approximately every other day. She also reports eating a lot of Easter candy over the weekend, which may have contributed to her elevated blood sugar levels.\n\nFindings\nVital signs reveal a blood pressure of 172/98 mmHg. The patient reports no shortness of breath. Physical examination reveals slight edema in the upper extremities and pitting edema of 1+ in the lower extremities bilaterally. A two out of six systolic ejection murmur is auscultated. Lung sounds are clear bilaterally. The heart rate is within normal limits. Oxygenation is adequate. No jugular venous distention is noted.\n\nAssessment\nThe patient presents with uncontrolled hypertension and elevated blood glucose levels. Further investigation is warranted to determine the underlying causes and optimize management.\n\nPlan\nI will continue your current medication regimen. I want to really encourage that you do take that everyday, maybe set a reminder like on your iPhone a lot for your reminders and things maybe we can go ahead and do that get a reminder make sure that you take that everyday. I would like to monitor your blood pressure three times a week. I recommend you purchase a blood pressure monitor at home. I also want to refer a nutritionist to help you with dietary changes, particularly reducing sodium intake. Finally, I will increase your metformin dosage to 1500 mg and schedule a follow-up appointment in one month to assess your progress and adjust the treatment plan as needed. Please let me know if you have any questions.",
  "reference_summary": "CHIEF COMPLAINT\n\nHeadache and high blood pressure.\n\nREVIEW OF SYSTEMS\n\nRespiratory: Denies shortness of breath.\nCardiovascular: Denies chest pain.\nNeurological: Reports blurry vision, dizziness, and headaches.\n\nVITALS\n\nBlood pressure today was 172/98. Oxygenation is within normal limits.\n\nPHYSICAL EXAM\n\nNeck\n- General Examination: No jugular venous distention. No carotid bruits.\n\nRespiratory\n- Auscultation of Lungs: Clear bilaterally.\n\nCardiovascular\n- Auscultation of Heart: Regular rate. Slight 2/6 systolic ejection murmur, unchanged from last year.\n\nMusculoskeletal\n- Examination: Slight edema to bilateral upper extremities. 1+ pitting edema noted in the bilateral lower extremities.\n\nASSESSMENT AND PLAN\n\n1. Hypertension, uncontrolled.\n- Medical Reasoning: The patient's blood pressure is is elevated.\n- Patient Education and Counseling: We discussed that this could be multifactorial; for example, her diet, her medications regimen, or the medication she is currently on could be a factor in her elevated blood pressure. I encouraged the patient to take her current medication regimen today. I encouraged her to monitor her blood pressure 3 times a week. We also discussed the patient speaking to our nutritionist to help her diet. I recommended a DASH diet.\n- Medical Treatment: She will continue her current medication regimen.\n\n2. Type 2 diabetes.\n- Medical Reasoning: The patient's diabetes is uncontrolled.\n- Patient Education and Counseling: I advised the patient to continue taking her blood sugars to make sure that the change in medication is effective.\n- Medical Treatment: Increase metformin to 1500 mg.\n\nPatient Agreements: The patient understands and agrees with the recommended medical treatment plan.\n\nINSTRUCTIONS\n\nThe patient will follow up in 4 weeks.",
